english:
  title: Record of the Hall of Gathering Elders
  author: Kim Il-son
  language: eng
  text: |-
    This hall takes its name 'Gathering of Elders' from the assemblies of the village fathers. What do they gather to do? To drink wine, to practice archery, to study the way—all such gatherings. The hall stands north of the prefectural city, built some ten years past by Kim Sun-son upon an ancient foundation. Though many have proposed since ancestral times that we maintain such institutions, each was abandoned soon after establishment, only to fall into ruin once more. The practices of drinking, archery, and study were never neglected by the court, yet our village lacked those willing to shoulder such duties, and so this hall became merely an empty structure standing alone.

    In the spring of the gyeongyu year, the court, concerned that rustic customs had departed from the ancient way, restored the system of Local Preservation and established the Village Elder. Five officials for prefectures, four for counties, three for districts—each chosen from the most respected of their domains to bear this weight. Kim Hae being a prefecture, we gathered: former magistrate of Ui-seong Kim Gye-geum, former supervisor of Cheongsan Baek Gye-yeong, former ritual officer Bae Hyeong, former attendant Song Suk-haeng, and my elder cousin, the scholar Kim Baek-gyeon—five souls, all pillars of our prefecture. Whenever public matters arise in the village, we gather in this hall to deliberate.

    Our prefecture was once Garak, where King Suro's tomb rests beyond the western gate. The government forbids the cutting of wood and grazing of animals there. By custom, the village fathers gather each year with proper offerings, and the people share in the blessing—a practice honored through time. I am of Kim Hae, descended from those who claim lineage to King Suro, though the details fade into distance. When I pass the tomb, I hesitate to claim kinship, remembering how even Guo Ziyi once doubted his own ancestry. Yet I follow the village people to arrange the ritual vessels.

    Last winter, returning from the fields of Do-ju, I arrived to find the village assembled for the blessing ceremony. I approached the elders in the hall and bowed. Kim the Elder greeted me, saying, "This is the custom of our people, long inherited. Does it not perhaps conflict with ancient propriety?" I replied, "How could it conflict? Since ancient times, whenever emperors and sage-kings have departed, their people erect temples. The records tell of shrines to Yao, Shun, and Yu the Great, and later to the founders of Han and the ancestors of Shu. Commoners may petition and give thanks, and offer sacrifice—not perhaps sanctioned by canonical texts, but in this the people preserve affection across a thousand years and kindle reverence that cannot be forbidden.

    "I have learned that King Suro founded his state in the eighteenth year of the Jianwu era, reigning through eleven generations for four hundred years, until the final king submitted to Silla and the kingdom ceased. More than a thousand years have passed; the royal line has vanished, and the blessings have dried. Yet the villagers still do not neglect their offerings. This is because King Suro was the first ruler of our people, and repaying his kindness is not something we can abandon. This is the beautiful custom of our village, and it is fitting that we preserve it through all generations."

    Kim the Elder said, "Well spoken. The state has restored this institution precisely to perfect our customs, and you have recognized it as such. Thus does this gathering shine with purpose in this hall. Since I have named it the Gathering of Elders, you must write its record." I rose and said further:

    "Those gathered here today are kinfolk and cousins only. In fostering harmony among us, we shall leave nothing undone. Yet know that every village has its customs, and customs, though long inherited, are mixed—some beautiful, some not. The beautiful customs, though born not of imperial decree, we cannot abandon. The ugly customs, though descended from old habit, we absolutely must not keep. Is it not the duty of elders to guide the youth of the village toward what is good and away from what is ill?

    "Today's Local Preservation mirrors the ancient Village Master who taught through threefold instruction and eightfold correction. Where father fails as father, son as son, brother as brother, sister as sister, husband as husband, wife as wife—where kinship falters and bonds break, where the low slander the high and officials prey upon the people—these matters fall within our watch. We must guide, admonish, and rouse them. For the grave offenses, we report to the magistrate. Thus shall we perfect our village's virtue and restore our people, after scattering, to the pure and generous way of King Suro. Then returning to this hall, raising a cup of spring wine in peace, we achieve not merely the village's fortune, but the state's.

    "The former prefect Lee generously provided funds for the tomb's maintenance. Now Prefect Kim, being of our village, ensures that all things tend toward its betterment. The elders rightly place their hopes in such men. My elder brother Baek-gyeon has built five chambers west of this hall with fields to support the rites and rooms for purification. With grain offerings properly made, will King Suro not accept? After the sacrifice, when we feast in fellowship, shall the elders not rejoice? In time, with white hair, I too shall become an elder of this hall."

    Thereupon he composed a song to summon the god, singing with the elders:

    The crimson cord falls to earth,
    its lineage threads on and on.
    The nine leaders lack a master—
    heaven sends one down.
    Upon the sea a kingdom fixed,
    four hundred years it spans.
    All the people in their households,
    generation after generation—
    when the seasons turn, they offer,
    the fathers gather running.
    The divine crow cries and scatters,
    ancient trees on barren ground.
    The ritual vessels stand in beauty,
    millet and grain release their fragrance.
    Pipe and drum sound forth—
    unheard, unseen, yet
    the spirit comes like cloud.
    Drunk and sated, serene, descending—
    why should blessing skip our people?
    Our people receive this gift,
    and taste both joy and peace.
    White-haired, locks thick with age,
    the cane sounds clear and bright.
    Dance and song year upon year—
    may they never, ever end.
  footnotes:
    - 'King Suro: legendary founder of Gaya, one of the Three Kingdoms of ancient Korea, believed to have ruled from 42 CE. Gaya was eventually absorbed into Silla.'
    - The 'threefold instruction and eightfold correction' refers to traditional Confucian methods of governance and moral education used by village administrators.
    - The reference to Guo Ziyi and questionable ancestry reflects the author's humble restraint about claiming descent from the ancient royal line.
